# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>The Daimyo emerged from the reconstruction of Luthien Armor Works following the devastating Clan assault on Luthien in 3052. With the Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery desperate for replacement BattleMechs and the factory complex in ruins, LAW engineers pressed forward with new designs incorporating both recovered and newly developed technologies. First produced in February 3053, the Daimyo carries the distinction of being the first entirely new BattleMech design to roll off the rebuilt Luthien Armor Works production lines. Filling the role of a medium command 'Mech for light and medium lances, the forty-ton Daimyo was designed to operate alongside existing Combine workhorses such as the Panther and Wolf Trap. Named for the feudal Japanese warlord title, the design reflects the Combine's cultural heritage while serving as a tangible symbol of the Dragon's resilience. Production has remained exclusive to Luthien Armor Works on Luthien, with the design seeing service primarily within DCMS formations and Free Rasalhague Republic units.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Daimyo's weapon mix provides effective engagement capability across all firing ranges. A Lord's Light 2 extended-range particle projection cannon mounted in the left arm serves as the primary armament, giving the 'Mech the ability to strike at extreme distances. For close-quarters engagements, two Victory 23R medium lasers in the right arm deliver reliable damage, supplemented by a Shannon SH-60 SRM-6 rack embedded in the right torso carrying a generous ammunition supply. This diverse armament encourages tactical flexibility among MechWarriors, though traditional tacticians have noted the design attempts to fill too many roles for a medium chassis.</p><p>Powered by a Nissan 200 fusion engine, the Daimyo achieves a respectable top speed of eighty-six kilometers per hour, matching or exceeding many medium 'Mechs of comparable tonnage. However, the absence of jump jets limits its tactical mobility in rough terrain, a notable shortcoming compared to most light and medium designs of its era. Luthien Armor Works elected to install double heat sinks following the controversy surrounding standard heat sinks in their PNT-10K Panther upgrade, though the Daimyo's weapons loadout can still overwhelm its heat dissipation capacity during sustained engagements. Starshield ferro-fibrous armor provides substantial protection for the chassis weight, allowing the 'Mech to absorb remarkable punishment for its size, but the lack of CASE protecting the SRM ammunition supply remains a potentially critical vulnerability.</p>

deployment:<p>A custom field refit built on the lawless world of Antallos around 3066, this variant began life as a captured DCMS Daimyo that was extensively modified using ComStar prototype technologies seized during a raid on a scientific expedition. The standard fusion engine was replaced with a captured two-hundred-rated light engine fitted with a supercharger, dramatically increasing the 'Mech's sprint capability. The Lord's Light 2 ER PPC gave way to a high-powered heavy PPC augmented by a PPC capacitor, delivering devastating concentrated firepower, while twin small X-pulse lasers replaced the original medium lasers and SRM rack for anti-infantry work. This one-of-a-kind modification was completed in a black-market tech shop on Antallos shortly before Clan Snow Raven seized that world.</p>

history:<p>The Daimyo's development was a direct response to the catastrophic losses sustained during the Clan Invasion. When Clan Smoke Jaguar and Clan Nova Cat launched their combined assault on Luthien in 3052, Luthien Armor Works suffered severe damage to its manufacturing facilities. Though the Clans ultimately failed to capture the Draconis Combine's capital, the DCMS faced acute shortages of frontline BattleMechs, making reconstruction of the LAW complex a matter of national survival. Engineers at LAW worked through the rebuilding period, incorporating both recovered Star League-era technologies and lessons learned from the Clan conflict into new designs.</p><p>The Daimyo entered service in February 3053 as the first new 'Mech to roll off the rebuilt production lines. The Sword of Light regiments received the initial production run, with the new design unveiled in a public ceremony on Luthien staged to demonstrate the Combine's industrial recovery and resolve to its citizens. The Daimyo subsequently spread to other DCMS formations across the Combine, filling gaps left by medium-weight units destroyed during the initial Clan campaigns. Deployed as a command 'Mech in light and medium lances, it worked effectively alongside Panthers and Wolf Traps already fielded by the Sword of Light.</p><p>During the Draconis March crisis, the Fifteenth Dieron Regulars employed Daimyos extensively in counterattacks against Draconis March forces that had launched an unauthorized assault against the Combine. These operations carried the Regulars as far as the Federated Commonwealth world of Addicks before the arrival of the Twelfth Deneb Light Cavalry and the mercenary Twelfth Vegan Rangers forced them to withdraw.</p><p>As part of the united front against the Clans forged on Outreach, Coordinator Theodore Kurita authorized the beleaguered Free Rasalhague Republic to purchase Combine military equipment. Many Daimyos were subsequently allocated to the Republic's Second Freeman regiment, marking the design's first significant deployment outside traditional DCMS service. Luthien Armor Works continued to refine the design throughout the late 3050s and early 3060s, producing several variants addressing heat management and command capability. Production of all standard variants ceased following the Civil War era, with Luthien Armor Works' facilities later devastated during the Word of Blake Jihad.</p>

